<ul id="commtree_42091673"><li id="tree_42091865" class="comment oneline"><span class="ind"></span>
<div id="comment_status_42091865" class="commentstatus"></div>
<div id="comment_42091865" class="cw">
	<div id="comment_top_42091865" class="commentTop newcomment">
		<div class="title">
			<h4><a id="comment_link_42091865" name="comment_link_42091865" href="//news.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=3272951&amp;cid=42091865" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(42091865)" >Re:</a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_42091865" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 42091865); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>3</a>)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a href="//slashdot.org/~diamondmagic">diamondmagic</a>  <span class="uid"><a href="//slashdot.org/~diamondmagic">(877411)</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_42091865"></span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_42091865"><p>I think you're missing the fact that there's no such thing as a "deflationary spiral". Likewise, inflationary spirals don't happen out of the blue, not without an influx of new money to bid up prices.</p><p>If people knew for a fact that prices were going to be spiraling upward at a constant rate for the next period of time, speculators would bid up prices to that level <i>in the present</i>, plus the cost of time (interest). This is a <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Black%E2%80%93Scholes" title="wikipedia.org">mathematical theorem<span class="substr"> </span></a> [wikipedia.org] </p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_42091865">

</div>
</div>

<div id="replyto_42091865"></div>

<ul id="group_42091865">
	<li id="hiddens_42091865" class="hide"></li>
